<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="570" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,381,768]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,453,479]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">Distribution</emphasis>
. Most common in the Atlantic Ocean and Mediterranean Sea, but has also been recordeed from the Pacific Ocean SE of 
<collectingCountry box="[381,448,490,516]" name="Japan" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">Japan</collectingCountry>
, and in the tropical waters of the East Pacific, probably including California (
<bibRefCitation author="Vinogradov, M. E. &amp; Volkov, A. F. &amp; Semenova, T. N." pageId="7" pageNumber="570" refId="ref14930" refString="Vinogradov, M. E., Volkov, A. F. &amp; Semenova, T. N. (1996) Hyperiid amphipods (Amphipoda, Hyperiidea) of the world oceans. Smithsonian Institution Libraries, Siegel-Causey, D., Scientific Editor, Washington D. C. and Oxonian Press Pvt. Ltd., New Delhi, 632 pp. [English translation of the 1982 Russian original]" type="book" year="1996">
Vinogradov 
<emphasis box="[151,200,526,552]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">et al</emphasis>
. 1996
</bibRefCitation>
). It is absent from the Indian Ocean (
<bibRefCitation author="Zeidler, W." box="[689,840,526,552]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" pagination="1 - 104" refId="ref15058" refString="Zeidler, W. (2003) A review of the Hyperiidean amphipod superfamily Vibilioidea Bowman &amp; Gruner, 1973 (Crustacea: Amphipoda: Hyperiidea). Zootaxa, 280, 1 - 104. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 280.1.1" type="journal article" year="2003">Zeidler 2003</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="570" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,381,768]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,562,588]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">Remarks</emphasis>
. The Californian records were based on juvenile specimens (
<bibRefCitation author="Vinogradov, M. E. &amp; Volkov, A. F. &amp; Semenova, T. N." box="[1033,1311,562,589]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" refId="ref14930" refString="Vinogradov, M. E., Volkov, A. F. &amp; Semenova, T. N. (1996) Hyperiid amphipods (Amphipoda, Hyperiidea) of the world oceans. Smithsonian Institution Libraries, Siegel-Causey, D., Scientific Editor, Washington D. C. and Oxonian Press Pvt. Ltd., New Delhi, 632 pp. [English translation of the 1982 Russian original]" type="book" year="1996">
Vinogradov 
<emphasis box="[1178,1232,562,588]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">et al</emphasis>
. 1996
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Gasca, R. &amp; Browne, W. E." pageId="7" pageNumber="570" pagination="1767 - 1775" refId="ref12534" refString="Gasca, R. &amp; Browne, W. E. (2018) Symbiotic associations of crustaceans and a pycnogonid with gelatinous zooplankton in the Gulf of California. Marine Biodiversity, 48 (4), 1767 - 1775. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 12526 - 017 - 0668 - 5" type="journal article" year="2018">Gasca &amp; Browne (2018)</bibRefCitation>
found some juveniles associated with 
<taxonomicName authority="Forskal, 1775" authorityName="Forskal" authorityYear="1775" box="[754,1075,597,625]" class="Thaliacea" family="Salpidae" genus="Salpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Salpida" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="maxima">
<emphasis box="[754,914,598,624]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">Salpa maxima</emphasis>
Forskål, 1775
</taxonomicName>
. Specimens observed herein are also juveniles and there is a possibility they are in fact juveniles (8.5 mm total length) of 
<taxonomicName authority="Spence Bate &amp; Westwood, 1868" authorityName="Spence Bate &amp; Westwood" authorityYear="1868" class="Malacostraca" family="Vibiliidae" genus="Vibilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="borealis">
<emphasis box="[1168,1288,634,660]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">V. borealis</emphasis>
Spence Bate &amp; Westwood, 1868
</taxonomicName>
, a very similar species which has been recorded in the Mexican Pacific by 
<bibRefCitation author="Gasca, R. &amp; Franco-Gordo, C. &amp; Godinez-Dominguez, E. &amp; Suarez-Morales, E." box="[1215,1433,670,696]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" pagination="123 - 139" refId="ref13150" refString="Gasca, R., Franco-Gordo, C., Godinez-Dominguez, E. &amp; Suarez-Morales, E. (2012) Hyperiid amphipod community in the Eastern Tropical Pacific before, during, and after El Nino 1997 - 1998. Marine Ecology Progress Series, 455, 123 - 139. https: // doi. org / 10.3354 / meps 09571" type="journal article" year="2012">
Gasca 
<emphasis box="[1291,1340,670,696]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">et al</emphasis>
. (2012)
</bibRefCitation>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Vinogradov, M. E. &amp; Volkov, A. F. &amp; Semenova, T. N." box="[151,428,706,733]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" refId="ref14930" refString="Vinogradov, M. E., Volkov, A. F. &amp; Semenova, T. N. (1996) Hyperiid amphipods (Amphipoda, Hyperiidea) of the world oceans. Smithsonian Institution Libraries, Siegel-Causey, D., Scientific Editor, Washington D. C. and Oxonian Press Pvt. Ltd., New Delhi, 632 pp. [English translation of the 1982 Russian original]" type="book" year="1996">
Vinogradov 
<emphasis box="[290,340,706,732]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">et al</emphasis>
. (1996)
</bibRefCitation>
recorded males and females of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bovallius" authorityYear="1887" box="[785,911,706,732]" class="Malacostraca" family="Vibiliidae" genus="Vibilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gibbosa">
<emphasis box="[785,911,706,732]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">V. gibbosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of 
<quantity box="[949,1014,706,732]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" unit="mm" value="7.0">7 mm</quantity>
and 
<quantity box="[1068,1133,706,732]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" unit="mm" value="8.0">8 mm</quantity>
only, respectively. Genetic studies could be necessary to help define which species occur in the northern hemisphere.
</paragraph>
